Do you want subtitles for any video?
-=[ ai.OpenSubtitles.com ]=-

13
00:01:25.169 --> 00:01:26.378
Hello!

14
00:01:26.378 --> 00:01:28.714
[speaks French]

15
00:01:29.214 --> 00:01:30.883
[in French] Help!

16
00:01:30.883 --> 00:01:32.342
Anyone?

17
00:01:35.179 --> 00:01:36.889
[footsteps approaching]

18
00:01:38.265 --> 00:01:39.266
[sniffs]

19
00:01:47.733 --> 00:01:50.277
[in English] Fuck! Okay. Okay. okay.

20
00:01:51.361 --> 00:01:52.613
Yeah. Yeah.

21
00:01:54.114 --> 00:01:56.033
All right. who are you. huh?

22
00:01:56.033 --> 00:01:57.743
What am I doing here?

23
00:01:57.743 --> 00:01:59.912
And why did you hit me in the head?

24
00:01:59.912 --> 00:02:01.747
Did we need that? Hmm?

25
00:02:03.916 --> 00:02:05.709
Uh... Uh...

26
00:02:05.709 --> 00:02:07.377
[in French] Who are you? Hmm?

27
00:02:08.419 --> 00:02:09.795
What are you doing?

28
00:02:11.965 --> 00:02:13.509
Are you French?

29
00:02:13.509 --> 00:02:15.636
[in English]
Someone is coming to talk to you.

30
00:02:16.929 --> 00:02:18.388
Who is? Who's coming to talk to me?

31
00:02:18.889 --> 00:02:21.308
- [inhales sharply. clicks tongue]
- Fuck. Okay. Yeah.

32
00:02:21.808 --> 00:02:23.185
Who's coming to talk to me?

33
00:02:26.355 --> 00:02:28.398
Huh? Did you take my phone?

34
00:02:29.233 --> 00:02:30.442
Did you... Wait. wait!

35
00:02:32.569 --> 00:02:35.656
Can you... [grunts] Fucking.

36
00:02:36.490 --> 00:02:37.699
<i>Merde!</i>

37
00:02:39.326 --> 00:02:40.327
[sighs]

38
00:02:43.956 --> 00:02:45.666
Shit.

39
00:02:46.834 --> 00:02:49.837
["Strange Game" playing]

40
00:03:35.465 --> 00:03:39.094
[Catherine] David. uh.
here's another cup of tea.

41
00:03:41.013 --> 00:03:42.931
Well. I hope this one's strong enough.

42
00:03:45.100 --> 00:03:47.853
Charles used to like his tea so weak
I used to say.

43
00:03:48.687 --> 00:03:50.814
"Do you want some tea with your milk?"

44
00:03:52.274 --> 00:03:53.692
Do you remember Charles?

45
00:03:55.944 --> 00:03:57.237
David?

46
00:03:57.237 --> 00:03:58.405
I killed him.

47
00:03:59.364 --> 00:04:01.074
- River.
- No.

48
00:04:01.575 --> 00:04:04.620
No. that was someone
who looked like him. Remember?

49
00:04:06.371 --> 00:04:08.207
Someone who looked like him?

50
00:04:10.167 --> 00:04:12.211
Dear God. what have I done?

51
00:04:12.211 --> 00:04:14.755
Uh. David. that was self-defense.

52
00:04:16.882 --> 00:04:21.011
No. I... [sighs. pants] I did it for River.

53
00:04:21.011 --> 00:04:24.890
[breathes shakily] To protect him.
To protect River.

54
00:04:26.850 --> 00:04:27.893
Where is he?

55
00:04:29.061 --> 00:04:32.773
Hmm? Where's my boy?

56
00:04:33.398 --> 00:04:35.526
[breathes shakily]
Why did he leave me here?

57
00:04:35.526 --> 00:04:36.818
- [panting]
- David?

58
00:04:39.321 --> 00:04:40.322
Who are you?

59
00:04:40.822 --> 00:04:42.658
Oh. I'm Catherine Standish.

60
00:04:42.658 --> 00:04:44.535
I used to work with River.

61
00:04:44.535 --> 00:04:47.579
And. uh. before that.
I worked for Charles Partner.

62
00:04:48.539 --> 00:04:50.499
No. No. I don't remember you.

63
00:04:50.499 --> 00:04:51.583
Oh.

64
00:04:52.292 --> 00:04:53.710
You knew Charles. you say?

65
00:04:53.710 --> 00:04:55.712
- Yes. I was his PA.
- I...

66
00:04:55.712 --> 00:04:57.965
And then I was Jackson's PA.

67
00:04:59.883 --> 00:05:00.884
The bomb.

68
00:05:02.261 --> 00:05:03.470
All those people.

69
00:05:04.638 --> 00:05:07.307
- All those poor people.
- No. David. The bomb wasn't you.

70
00:05:07.307 --> 00:05:08.809
[knocks on door]

71
00:05:08.809 --> 00:05:10.018
David.

72
00:05:13.772 --> 00:05:15.899
- Oh.
- [pants] I must speak to First Desk.

73
00:05:15.899 --> 00:05:17.025
You can't go to the Park.

74
00:05:17.025 --> 00:05:18.569
- River doesn't want that.
- No. no. no.

75
00:05:18.569 --> 00:05:19.862
- Get your hands off me.
- No. David.

76
00:05:19.862 --> 00:05:22.155
- Don't touch me!
- I'm sorry.

77
00:05:22.155 --> 00:05:23.991
I have to talk to First Desk.

78
00:05:23.991 --> 00:05:26.159
I have to tell them what happened.

79
00:05:26.159 --> 00:05:28.495
- [pants] What's coming.
- What's coming?

80
00:05:28.495 --> 00:05:29.580
What happened?

81
00:05:30.455 --> 00:05:31.582
The bomb.

82
00:05:32.416 --> 00:05:33.250
River.

83
00:05:33.250 --> 00:05:37.880
I have... [stammers]
Why am I talking to you?

84
00:05:38.672 --> 00:05:39.673
I remember you.

85
00:05:39.673 --> 00:05:42.426
- You're just a bloody secretary.
- [scoffs]

86
00:05:42.426 --> 00:05:44.970
- Get me First Desk.
- David. David. listen.

87
00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:47.472
Listen. First Desk is very busy. Yes?

88
00:05:47.472 --> 00:05:49.266
- I mean. you know what it's like.
- No. no. no.

89
00:05:49.266 --> 00:05:52.144
They'll talk to me. They'll talk to me.
I used to run the damn place.

90
00:05:52.144 --> 00:05:53.520
I know you did.

91
00:05:53.520 --> 00:05:58.650
But at this time of day. he'll be
reading the cables from Berlin. won't he?

92
00:05:59.234 --> 00:06:04.198
Berlin? Oh. yes. Yes. of course.
That... [chuckles]

93
00:06:04.198 --> 00:06:05.324
- And he...
- The schedule.

94
00:06:05.324 --> 00:06:07.618
That's right.
And he's got to get that right.

95
00:06:07.618 --> 00:06:09.995
I mean. agents in play.
awaiting instructions.

96
00:06:09.995 --> 00:06:11.163
We can't interrupt that.

97
00:06:11.163 --> 00:06:12.956
No. no. It's very dangerous.

98
00:06:12.956 --> 00:06:17.544
So. if you will allow me.
I will call the Park right now.

99
00:06:17.544 --> 00:06:20.797
and I will get you the first
available appointment after that.

100
00:06:20.797 --> 00:06:21.715
You can do that?

101
00:06:21.715 --> 00:06:24.218
[scoffs] I'm a secretary.
That's what I do.

102
00:06:24.218 --> 00:06:26.053
- [chuckles] Here. sit.
- [chuckles]

103
00:06:26.720 --> 00:06:27.721
Okay.

104
00:06:28.472 --> 00:06:30.641
- Oh. Yeah. [chuckles]
- Here's your tea.

105
00:06:30.641 --> 00:06:31.934
Thank you.

106
00:06:31.934 --> 00:06:33.143
I'll be back in a minute.

107
00:06:33.143 --> 00:06:34.728
- It's very kind of you.
- You're welcome.

108
00:06:34.728 --> 00:06:37.940
I... I need to speak to First Desk.

109
00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:39.024
Yes.

110
00:06:45.989 --> 00:06:47.824
- [crockery clattering]
- It's my fault.

111
00:06:48.742 --> 00:06:49.743
[sniffs]

112
00:06:50.994 --> 00:06:52.454
It's all my fault.

113
00:06:58.752 --> 00:07:01.755
[panting]

114
00:07:19.940 --> 00:07:21.942
[panting]

115
00:07:25.237 --> 00:07:26.738
Who's upstairs?

116
00:07:27.281 --> 00:07:28.907
The usual bunch of dead weights.

117
00:07:28.907 --> 00:07:32.327
Shit rises to the top in this building
with the gold at the bottom.

118
00:07:32.953 --> 00:07:35.205
Although. you have the top office.
so I'll take that back.

119
00:07:35.205 --> 00:07:37.583
Listen. you tit. in the last hour.

120
00:07:37.583 --> 00:07:41.378
someone walked up those stairs
in shoes that are outside your salary.

121
00:07:41.378 --> 00:07:42.379
Who?

122
00:07:42.379 --> 00:07:44.047
Well. it's not my fault.

123
00:07:44.047 --> 00:07:45.674
I didn't know who she was.

124
00:07:46.592 --> 00:07:47.676
Oh.

125
00:07:47.676 --> 00:07:50.304
And if I'd had known.
I couldn't have stopped her.

126
00:07:50.304 --> 00:07:52.639
[footsteps departing]

127
00:07:58.395 --> 00:08:00.230
[Jackson] Were you here when she came in?

128
00:08:00.230 --> 00:08:02.357
No. that's not my fault.

129
00:08:03.275 --> 00:08:04.902
Is River headed to Lavande?

130
00:08:04.902 --> 00:08:07.988
[sighs] Go to Catherine's.
get her to move David Cartwright.

131
00:08:07.988 --> 00:08:09.948
David's with Catherine?

132
00:08:11.950 --> 00:08:14.578
- What about River?
- [footsteps departing]

133
00:08:22.586 --> 00:08:24.129
Well. this wasn't in the diary.

134
00:08:24.129 --> 00:08:26.715
[sighs] Lucky I have a free slot.

135
00:08:26.715 --> 00:08:29.801
Has anyone offered you tea or coffee?

136
00:08:29.801 --> 00:08:31.845
- No.
- Yeah. well. it's just as well.

137
00:08:31.845 --> 00:08:34.515
I think there's
something dead in the water tank.

138
00:08:35.097 --> 00:08:37.476
[sighs] So. how can I help?

139
00:08:37.476 --> 00:08:38.559
I think you know why I'm here.

140
00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:43.649
[stammers] You've not been relegated
to Slough House already. have you?

141
00:08:43.649 --> 00:08:46.276
What the fuck did you do?
Get caught drinking on the job?

142
00:08:46.276 --> 00:08:47.778
You can drop the act.

143
00:08:47.778 --> 00:08:49.613
I know you're
not the shambling fool you appear.

144
00:08:50.197 --> 00:08:52.074
Blood work come back. has it?

145
00:08:53.158 --> 00:08:54.243
Well. what can I say?

146
00:08:54.243 --> 00:08:56.411
[mumbles] He's my joe.

147
00:08:56.411 --> 00:08:58.539
He-He-He wanted
everyone to think he was dead.

148
00:08:58.539 --> 00:09:00.749
and I helped keep it that way
for as long as I could.

149
00:09:00.749 --> 00:09:04.169
He might be your joe. but he's MI5's agent
and he was present at a murder scene.

150
00:09:04.169 --> 00:09:06.505
Maybe he even pulled the trigger.
I'm bringing him in.

151
00:09:06.505 --> 00:09:07.923
Uh. well. be my guest.

152
00:09:07.923 --> 00:09:09.550
I don't know where the fuck he is.

153
00:09:09.550 --> 00:09:11.176
So. you can put the thumbscrews on me.

154
00:09:11.176 --> 00:09:13.053
'cause that's the only
answer you're gonna get.

155
00:09:13.053 --> 00:09:15.222
I'm taking you in for
obstructing an investigation. Get up.

156
00:09:15.222 --> 00:09:16.682
Nah. I'm good here. thanks.

157
00:09:16.682 --> 00:09:19.226
[smacks lips] I got a full day
of fuck all to get through.

158
00:09:19.226 --> 00:09:20.978
Well. the carload of Dogs
I'm about to call

159
00:09:20.978 --> 00:09:22.396
might get in the way of that.

160
00:09:23.772 --> 00:09:26.733
[sighs] Well. I wouldn't
want people to think

161
00:09:26.733 --> 00:09:29.611
they had to send a bunch of men
to do a woman's job.

162
00:09:30.988 --> 00:09:33.824
Now. uh. cuffs won't be necessary.
Come on.

163
00:09:33.824 --> 00:09:38.245
I'd rather not take any chances with a man
who looks like he gropes people on buses.

164
00:09:40.831 --> 00:09:43.125
You're being hurtful about my appearance.

165
00:09:43.125 --> 00:09:45.377
I might have to call HR.

166
00:09:50.674 --> 00:09:52.634
Look. I get why you're angry.

167
00:09:54.052 --> 00:09:58.140
[sighs] You would have told Taverner
that River was dead.

168
00:09:58.140 --> 00:10:01.518
and she did a little jig
and now you gotta go back and tell her

169
00:10:01.518 --> 00:10:03.812
that the most troublesome agent
is alive and well

170
00:10:03.812 --> 00:10:05.772
and in the wind doing fuck knows what.

171
00:10:06.648 --> 00:10:11.403
So. by way of amends.
I'm happy to give you David Cartwright.

172
00:10:11.403 --> 00:10:12.738
Why would you do that?

173
00:10:13.322 --> 00:10:16.658
[panting] Because going to the Park
is like being in IKEA.

174
00:10:16.658 --> 00:10:18.911
You can never get
out of the fucking place.

175
00:10:19.536 --> 00:10:20.913
Go on then.

176
00:10:20.913 --> 00:10:21.997
[sighs]

177
00:10:23.707 --> 00:10:25.667
[scoffs] Do I look like an idiot?

178
00:10:25.667 --> 00:10:32.591
[pants] You know. talking about your looks
could get me into all sorts of trouble.

179
00:10:32.591 --> 00:10:35.385
You'd burn David Cartwright to avoid
being taken in yourself?

180
00:10:35.385 --> 00:10:38.180
[sighs] River's my joe.
But Cartwright's a piece of shit.

181
00:10:38.180 --> 00:10:42.976
The idea of him sitting in a basement cell
stirs my nethers.

182
00:10:44.311 --> 00:10:45.187
Where is he?

183
00:10:45.187 --> 00:10:47.481
[panting]

184
00:10:51.235 --> 00:10:52.444
[Flyte sighs]

185
00:10:52.444 --> 00:10:54.696
[Roddy breathes heavily. grunting]

186
00:10:59.743 --> 00:11:01.370
- [footsteps approach]
- Hey.

187
00:11:03.664 --> 00:11:04.957
Hey. apologies.

188
00:11:04.957 --> 00:11:06.083
What for?

189
00:11:06.667 --> 00:11:08.460
Well. I didn't realize you were a Dog.

190
00:11:09.336 --> 00:11:11.922
Uh. I mean. obviously you're not a dog.

191
00:11:13.257 --> 00:11:14.758
Where did you park your wings?

192
00:11:15.843 --> 00:11:17.219
Meaning you're an angel.

193
00:11:18.387 --> 00:11:23.725
In case you thought I was implying you
were a seagull or a... a crow.

194
00:11:25.435 --> 00:11:28.313
But with those legs.
you're more of a flamingo. aren't ya?

195
00:11:29.648 --> 00:11:31.066
[chuckles]

196
00:11:33.402 --> 00:11:34.236
[click]

197
00:11:36.113 --> 00:11:37.114
Hey!

198
00:11:40.742 --> 00:11:43.370
Well. I've actually got
a girlfriend anyway. so you lose.

199
00:11:43.871 --> 00:11:46.164
I can just slip this off. so...

200
00:11:48.166 --> 00:11:49.543
double lose.

201
00:11:49.543 --> 00:11:52.421
[grunts. panting]

202
00:11:53.755 --> 00:11:54.756
- Hi.
- [agent] Hi.

203
00:12:00.179 --> 00:12:01.180
[Claude clears throat]

204
00:12:03.807 --> 00:12:06.310
- Giti? Is... Is it Giti?
- Uh...

205
00:12:06.310 --> 00:12:07.936
- Is it Giti? It is.
- ...yeah. [chuckles]

206
00:12:07.936 --> 00:12:09.563
No. no. please. please. Please. sit down.

207
00:12:09.563 --> 00:12:11.607
- Sit down. No hierarchy here.
- Uh.

208
00:12:11.607 --> 00:12:13.317
[chuckles] All is one. I like to think...

209
00:12:13.317 --> 00:12:15.194
- [sighs]
- [clears throat] ...to myself.

210
00:12:15.194 --> 00:12:19.156
Um... Uh. it's just. uh. Diana Taverner
commended you to me for your...

211
00:12:19.156 --> 00:12:21.366
The work you did on the cold body case.

212
00:12:21.366 --> 00:12:23.202
And I wanted to say thank you very much.

213
00:12:23.202 --> 00:12:26.496
Thank you. [inhales sharply]
Such a relief it was a glitch.

214
00:12:26.496 --> 00:12:28.874
Yes. Yes. it was. Yeah.

215
00:12:28.874 --> 00:12:30.709
Gave us all
a bit of a scare though for a minute.

216
00:12:30.709 --> 00:12:32.920
Oh. I didn't mean to
cause any unnecessary panic.

217
00:12:32.920 --> 00:12:34.630
Oh. no. no. Totally necessary.

218
00:12:34.630 --> 00:12:37.841
I mean.
we've got to explore every possibility.

219
00:12:37.841 --> 00:12:40.594
And in fact. that actually got me
to thinking. because. um.

220
00:12:40.594 --> 00:12:43.764
I thought it would be a very good idea
to double-check the archives

221
00:12:43.764 --> 00:12:46.725
for any other glitches. you know.

222
00:12:46.725 --> 00:12:50.604
Anomalies in the. uh. cold body program.

223
00:12:50.604 --> 00:12:52.064
Uh. okay.

224
00:12:52.064 --> 00:12:54.816
[stammers]
I-I did actually suggest that to her.

225
00:12:55.400 --> 00:12:57.027
- Second Desk.
- Did you?

226
00:12:57.027 --> 00:13:00.364
Mm-hmm. And she said I'd be
better placed on current duties.

227
00:13:00.364 --> 00:13:01.448
- Did she? Yeah.
- Mmm.

228
00:13:01.448 --> 00:13:05.077
Well. she's absolutely right. of course.
From her perspective. [clears throat]

229
00:13:05.077 --> 00:13:07.663
I mean. she's running...
She's running live ops. isn't she?

230
00:13:07.663 --> 00:13:11.500
And with Westacres ongoing. she doesn't...
She doesn't have the bandwidth

231
00:13:11.500 --> 00:13:15.963
for this kind of. what should we say.
uh. speculative investigation.

232
00:13:16.755 --> 00:13:21.468
But I do and I would like you
to report direct to me.

233
00:13:22.302 --> 00:13:23.720
I'd love to.

234
00:13:24.471 --> 00:13:26.932
- Uh. love is probably the wrong word.
- Yeah. probably.

235
00:13:26.932 --> 00:13:29.101
- It will be okay with her. won't it?
- Yeah. that's a bit...

236
00:13:29.101 --> 00:13:30.936
Uh. I don't want to get in any trouble.

237
00:13:30.936 --> 00:13:33.564
No. no. no. keep this between ourselves.
I think.

238
00:13:33.564 --> 00:13:36.149
Uh. discretion being
the better part of valor.

239
00:13:36.149 --> 00:13:39.069
And you'll be getting us ahead
of any potential trouble.

240
00:13:39.069 --> 00:13:41.196
which would be a big help in fact.

241
00:13:41.196 --> 00:13:45.659
Uh. so if there's anything
that I can do to facilitate that.

242
00:13:45.659 --> 00:13:48.120
uh. please... please do tell me.

243
00:13:50.831 --> 00:13:51.915
Please. after you.

244
00:13:51.915 --> 00:13:54.084
- H-Have you been in here before?
- I haven't.

245
00:13:54.084 --> 00:13:55.752
- Oh. have you met Molly?
- No.

246
00:13:55.752 --> 00:13:59.840
Oh. a lot of fun. A lot of fun.
[chuckles] Uh...

247
00:14:02.134 --> 00:14:03.218
Oh.

248
00:14:04.052 --> 00:14:05.512
Oh. hello. Molly.

249
00:14:05.512 --> 00:14:07.097
[clicks tongue] Hello. Weasel.

250
00:14:07.097 --> 00:14:09.433
[laughing]

251
00:14:09.433 --> 00:14:12.060
Uh. Weasel's a term they use
to refer to those of us

252
00:14:12.060 --> 00:14:15.564
that use gaming programs
to refine long-term strategy.

253
00:14:15.564 --> 00:14:17.441
That's... That's actually what that means.

254
00:14:17.441 --> 00:14:20.235
You'll always be a Weasel to me.

255
00:14:21.028 --> 00:14:23.030
Yeah. Molly. I'm First Desk. all right?
[mumbles]

256
00:14:23.030 --> 00:14:25.199
Not appropriate. is it?

257
00:14:25.199 --> 00:14:28.035
- So... [clears throat] ...cold bodies?
- Yes.

258
00:14:28.035 --> 00:14:31.538
Yes. Giti here thinks that she may
have found one connected to Westacres.

259
00:14:32.497 --> 00:14:36.210
So. what I'd like her to do is to
double-check that there aren't

260
00:14:36.210 --> 00:14:41.423
any of our old cold bodies
out there in the world being used.

261
00:14:41.423 --> 00:14:42.674
You understand?

262
00:14:43.217 --> 00:14:46.637
If you wouldn't mind
affording her the run of this place.

263
00:14:46.637 --> 00:14:50.849
facilitating in any way that you can.
I'd appreciate that.

264
00:14:53.018 --> 00:14:55.395
Uh. thank you.

265
00:14:55.395 --> 00:14:57.397
Thank you so much. Giti. Thank you.

266
00:14:59.525 --> 00:15:03.195
I've had enough of games
between First and Second Desk.

267
00:15:04.029 --> 00:15:06.365
Yeah. me too. Well. it's funny.

268
00:15:06.365 --> 00:15:09.868
It's funny. because. um. who-who-who
do you think comes first in that?

269
00:15:09.868 --> 00:15:14.748
You know. when I say First Desk and
then I say Second Desk. who do you think...

270
00:15:14.748 --> 00:15:16.333
Diana Taverner.

271
00:15:26.426 --> 00:15:28.762
[mob speaking French]

272
00:15:30.347 --> 00:15:32.349
[dog barking in distance]

273
00:15:38.146 --> 00:15:40.691
[speaking French]

274
00:15:41.859 --> 00:15:44.236
Natasha! [speaks French]

275
00:15:45.946 --> 00:15:48.031
[speaks French]

276
00:15:48.031 --> 00:15:50.826
[both speak French]

277
00:15:50.826 --> 00:15:54.204
[speaking French]

278
00:15:55.205 --> 00:15:58.417
[door opens. closes]

279
00:15:59.376 --> 00:16:02.212
[footsteps approaching]

280
00:16:08.802 --> 00:16:10.429
[door unlocks]

281
00:16:17.936 --> 00:16:18.937
Who are you?

282
00:16:19.605 --> 00:16:21.356
Are you the person
who's been wanting to talk to me?

283
00:16:21.356 --> 00:16:23.984
We're the ones with the gun.
So. we ask the questions here.

284
00:16:24.943 --> 00:16:26.278
Okay.

285
00:16:26.278 --> 00:16:28.697
[Natasha] You look like
someone from Les Arbres.

286
00:16:28.697 --> 00:16:32.284
You have a passport with his photo in.
and you're not him.

287
00:16:33.535 --> 00:16:34.703
What were you doing there?

288
00:16:34.703 --> 00:16:37.247
I'm guessing from the fact
that he keeps pointing that at me

289
00:16:37.247 --> 00:16:39.750
that you didn't like this guy very much.

290
00:16:39.750 --> 00:16:41.460
So. maybe
he'll put it down when I tell you

291
00:16:41.460 --> 00:16:44.087
that he can't hurt anyone anymore
because he's dead.

292
00:16:50.511 --> 00:16:52.054
Why is he not putting the gun down?

293
00:16:54.723 --> 00:16:56.016
He was my son.

294
00:16:59.186 --> 00:17:00.479
How did he die?

295
00:17:02.314 --> 00:17:05.108
He turned up at my grandfather's
pretending to be me

296
00:17:05.901 --> 00:17:08.028
because he was going
to drown him in a bath.

297
00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:10.239
But then my grandfather shot him.

298
00:17:19.580 --> 00:17:21.415
[in French] It was bound to end that way.

299
00:17:22.542 --> 00:17:23.794
With a father like that.

300
00:17:25.878 --> 00:17:27.673
- [in English] Look. right.
- [gun cocks]

301
00:17:30.008 --> 00:17:32.386
I'm MI5. Okay?

302
00:17:34.388 --> 00:17:36.223
The British security service.

303
00:17:36.223 --> 00:17:37.474
We don't care.

304
00:17:38.475 --> 00:17:39.685
You... Just go.

305
00:17:41.270 --> 00:17:42.437
[stammers]

306
00:17:47.985 --> 00:17:49.236
Yes.

307
00:17:55.742 --> 00:17:56.577
Look. look.

308
00:17:56.577 --> 00:18:00.747
I-I-I... I'm sorry about your son.
but I-I need to know who he was.

309
00:18:00.747 --> 00:18:03.125
You've been asking to leave. now leave.

310
00:18:03.125 --> 00:18:04.918
You really need to stop
pointing that at me.

311
00:18:04.918 --> 00:18:07.087
- [mob speaking French]
- Okay? [stammers]

312
00:18:07.880 --> 00:18:09.047
[stammers] Wh-Who are they?

313
00:18:10.132 --> 00:18:11.216
They think you are Bertrand.

314
00:18:11.216 --> 00:18:14.178
Right. But I'm not Bertrand. am I?
Can you tell them that?

315
00:18:14.178 --> 00:18:17.181
- Tell them yourself.
- I'm... All right. look.

316
00:18:17.181 --> 00:18:18.348
Listen to me. all right?

317
00:18:19.433 --> 00:18:21.643
You see this? You see this man?

318
00:18:21.643 --> 00:18:23.604
The one next to your son?

319
00:18:24.396 --> 00:18:26.648
- [Natasha] Yeah.
- He was at Les Arbres too. right?

320
00:18:26.648 --> 00:18:27.983
- Yeah?
- [Natasha] Yeah.

321
00:18:27.983 --> 00:18:30.068
Well. you know the bomb in London?
The one at the shops?

322
00:18:30.068 --> 00:18:31.320
That was him.

323
00:18:31.820 --> 00:18:33.071
He set that off.

324
00:18:35.115 --> 00:18:36.617
And that could happen again.

325
00:18:37.910 --> 00:18:40.621
So. you need to tell me
who these people are

326
00:18:40.621 --> 00:18:42.039
and where I can find them.

327
00:18:47.920 --> 00:18:49.963
Catherine. it's Louisa. Again.

328
00:18:50.756 --> 00:18:54.051
Emma Flyte. new head Dog.
is on her way to you.

329
00:18:54.051 --> 00:18:56.970
She's after David Cartwright.
You need to get him out before she...

330
00:18:58.931 --> 00:18:59.932
Oh. shit.

331
00:19:01.141 --> 00:19:02.309
[sighs]

332
00:19:04.603 --> 00:19:07.564
[panting] Excuse me?

333
00:19:08.273 --> 00:19:10.108
Excuse me? Hi.

334
00:19:10.108 --> 00:19:13.904
[panting] I'm rea... I'm really sorry.
but I think someone's following me.

335
00:19:13.904 --> 00:19:17.449
Do... Do you think... Do you think you could
just walk with me to the end of the road?

336
00:19:17.449 --> 00:19:19.660
- [panting]
- Um. I-I can't see anyone.

337
00:19:19.660 --> 00:19:22.037
Oh. They're... They're probably hiding.

338
00:19:22.037 --> 00:19:24.623
I just... I was in the shop earlier
and I came back out.

339
00:19:24.623 --> 00:19:27.292
and I thought he had disappeared.
but then he was right behind me again.

340
00:19:27.960 --> 00:19:28.794
Not him. is it?

341
00:19:30.754 --> 00:19:32.798
No. no. no. no.
This guy is just... He's much younger.

342
00:19:32.798 --> 00:19:35.050
He's got really scary eyes.
and he's just really dangerous.

343
00:19:35.050 --> 00:19:37.511
Okay. Well. you're in luck.
'cause I'm with the security services.

344
00:19:37.511 --> 00:19:38.804
Oh. thank God. Can we walk?

345
00:19:38.804 --> 00:19:41.431
- [Flyte] My colleague will deal with it.
- Oh. okay.

346
00:19:41.431 --> 00:19:42.808
- Great. Thank you.
- Okay.

347
00:19:44.643 --> 00:19:47.312
- Is everything all right?
- Yeah. Uh. yeah.

348
00:19:47.312 --> 00:19:49.731
I was just. um.
speaking to your colleague.

349
00:19:49.731 --> 00:19:51.859
Uh... I thought someone was following me.
but they're not.

350
00:19:51.859 --> 00:19:53.026
- So. it's all...
- You sure?

351
00:19:53.026 --> 00:19:55.320
- Yeah. Thank you. Fuck's sake.
- Uh. you look familiar.

352
00:19:57.239 --> 00:20:00.075
Wow. Vulnerable woman
and you're trying it on?

353
00:20:00.075 --> 00:20:02.619
No. God. no. No.
I just feel like we've met. That is all.

354
00:20:02.619 --> 00:20:04.788
Right. You just stop right there
before I report you.

355
00:20:04.788 --> 00:20:06.081
- Okay?
- Yeah.

356
00:20:08.625 --> 00:20:09.626
So now you're following me?

357
00:20:10.210 --> 00:20:11.211
[scoffs]

358
00:20:12.713 --> 00:20:14.256
Just tryna help. man.

359
00:20:15.465 --> 00:20:18.385
- [doorbell rings]
- [door opens]

360
00:20:19.678 --> 00:20:21.555
Emma Flyte. Head of security for the Park.

361
00:20:21.555 --> 00:20:24.266
- [chattering on radio]
- Can I see some ID. please?

362
00:20:29.396 --> 00:20:31.023
[latch unlocks]

363
00:20:32.274 --> 00:20:34.067
- How can I help?
- You can let me inside.

364
00:20:35.027 --> 00:20:36.069
Do you have a warrant?

365
00:20:36.069 --> 00:20:37.863
You're still a member of the service.

366
00:20:37.863 --> 00:20:39.865
which means
you're subject to my jurisdiction.

367
00:20:39.865 --> 00:20:41.658
Which means I don't need a warrant.

368
00:20:41.658 --> 00:20:44.161
Except I resigned a while ago.

369
00:20:44.161 --> 00:20:46.121
Hmm. Yes. Not exactly.

370
00:20:46.121 --> 00:20:49.458
You handed in your resignation.
but the paperwork seems to have stalled.

371
00:20:49.458 --> 00:20:51.460
Remind me.
are you still receiving a salary?

372
00:20:51.460 --> 00:20:53.086
Receiving. not spending.

373
00:20:53.086 --> 00:20:56.089
Doesn't matter.
You're on the books. so open up.

374
00:21:05.807 --> 00:21:06.642
[sighs]

375
00:21:06.642 --> 00:21:09.770
[radio host] <i>...updates on the progress
of the Westacres investigation</i>

376
00:21:09.770 --> 00:21:11.355
<i>is the Deputy Commissioner...</i>

377
00:21:11.355 --> 00:21:13.440
[Flyte] Still keeping a hand in. I see.

378
00:21:13.440 --> 00:21:15.817
I'm allowed to keep up with the news.

379
00:21:15.817 --> 00:21:17.736
- Nice flat.
- Thank you.

380
00:21:17.736 --> 00:21:18.987
Quiet area too.

381
00:21:19.821 --> 00:21:21.406
And you're a reader.

382
00:21:21.406 --> 00:21:24.368
Nothing spoils a good book
faster than a lot of background noise.

383
00:21:24.368 --> 00:21:26.370
Unless it's unwelcome visitors.

384
00:21:27.996 --> 00:21:31.250
- Talking of visitors. where is he?
- Who?

385
00:21:32.709 --> 00:21:34.127
David Cartwright.

386
00:21:34.127 --> 00:21:38.090
Dav... I haven't seen
David Cartwright in over 20 years. so...

387
00:21:38.090 --> 00:21:39.800
Please don't go in there.

388
00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:41.969
Uh. why would he... Oh.

389
00:21:43.637 --> 00:21:46.181
I asked you not to come in here.

390
00:21:46.181 --> 00:21:48.350
I don't like strangers in my bedroom.

391
00:21:49.351 --> 00:21:51.228
Excuse me. [sighs]

392
00:21:52.396 --> 00:21:55.315
I'm sorry. but are we in some sort of
West End farce?

393
00:21:55.315 --> 00:21:57.401
- [sighs]
- Oh. for God's sake.

394
00:21:57.901 --> 00:21:58.861
[clicks tongue. sighs]

395
00:22:04.616 --> 00:22:05.951
Why is this locked?

396
00:22:05.951 --> 00:22:07.327
It's not. It's just stiff.

397
00:22:07.327 --> 00:22:10.831
You have to open it gently
or that happens. See?

398
00:22:11.498 --> 00:22:13.000
I've probably put too much in here.

399
00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:15.085
Look. who told you he was here?

400
00:22:15.085 --> 00:22:16.170
Jackson Lamb.

401
00:22:19.173 --> 00:22:22.009
Oh. well. he'll have sent you here
purely to distress me.

402
00:22:22.009 --> 00:22:23.343
We've had a falling out.

403
00:22:24.052 --> 00:22:26.930
I'm afraid you've been used. Miss Flyte.

404
00:22:26.930 --> 00:22:28.307
Just a moment.

405
00:22:29.224 --> 00:22:31.518
Good luck with finding David.

406
00:22:32.561 --> 00:22:36.231
You should try asking his grandson. River.
where he is.

407
00:22:46.200 --> 00:22:47.743
[Marcus] All right. Back in a bit.

408
00:22:48.493 --> 00:22:50.829
You know. it might be an idea
to hold on to that gun.

409
00:22:50.829 --> 00:22:52.247
Everyone's a target.

410
00:22:53.832 --> 00:22:57.127
Post-Westacres. we don't know where
or when the next attack will come.

411
00:22:59.046 --> 00:23:01.381
Put your headphones in.
and shut the fuck up.

412
00:23:02.090 --> 00:23:03.800
It's bad karma to sell it.

413
00:23:03.800 --> 00:23:06.220
[Marcus] It's bad karma to have
the Christmas decorations still up.

414
00:23:06.220 --> 00:23:08.680
Weapons on the street versus
tinsel-based superstition.

415
00:23:08.680 --> 00:23:09.681
Yeah. exactly the same.

416
00:23:09.681 --> 00:23:11.850
Look. I don't want to be doing this.
but I've got no choice.

417
00:23:11.850 --> 00:23:13.435
Cassie's already noticing
the unpaid bills.

418
00:23:13.435 --> 00:23:16.522
- It's a fucking nightmare.
- Of your own creation.

419
00:23:17.356 --> 00:23:19.608
- Look. I sort this. and I'm done.
- [phone ringing]

420
00:23:20.734 --> 00:23:22.194
For real this time.

421
00:23:22.194 --> 00:23:23.278
[scoffs]

422
00:23:25.489 --> 00:23:28.534
Hi. Can you come down and help me?

423
00:23:28.534 --> 00:23:30.077
Fuck off.

424
00:23:32.538 --> 00:23:33.664
[sighs]

425
00:23:34.665 --> 00:23:35.791
Ho wants help.

426
00:23:35.791 --> 00:23:38.001
Unless it's with assisting his suicide.
I'm not interested.

427
00:23:38.001 --> 00:23:39.336
[phone ringing]

428
00:23:40.921 --> 00:23:43.131
[Roddy] <i>Look. I'm handcuffed
to my weights machine.</i>

429
00:23:45.676 --> 00:23:46.677
[sighs]

430
00:23:49.513 --> 00:23:51.765
He's handcuffed to his weight machine.
Worth a look.

431
00:23:57.521 --> 00:24:00.190
- [footsteps approaching]
- [grunting]

432
00:24:00.190 --> 00:24:01.483
[Shirley chuckles]

433
00:24:01.483 --> 00:24:04.778
Was this an accident
or part of a wanking game?

434
00:24:05.612 --> 00:24:06.613
It was Flyte.

435
00:24:07.239 --> 00:24:08.073
Good on her.

436
00:24:08.073 --> 00:24:10.367
I'm not gonna bother asking why.
'cause I'm sure it was deserved.

437
00:24:10.367 --> 00:24:11.869
Look. are you gonna help me?

438
00:24:11.869 --> 00:24:12.995
No.

439
00:24:13.537 --> 00:24:14.538
[Shirley scoffs]

440
00:24:16.957 --> 00:24:18.375
What are you doing?

441
00:24:19.835 --> 00:24:20.669
[chuckles]

442
00:24:20.669 --> 00:24:23.839
I mean. at least leave him there overnight
or till he shits himself.

443
00:24:23.839 --> 00:24:25.007
[JK] I have to help him.

444
00:24:27.634 --> 00:24:29.803
No. you don't. [gasps]

445
00:24:30.470 --> 00:24:31.471
[Roddy chuckles]

446
00:24:32.264 --> 00:24:35.184
Do you want to know why
I'm going to free him?

447
00:24:35.726 --> 00:24:38.270
I want to know why
you're holding a knife to my throat.

448
00:24:38.270 --> 00:24:40.022
Well. before I was assigned here.

449
00:24:40.022 --> 00:24:44.193
I was handcuffed against my will
and tied to a chair for 72 hours.

450
00:24:44.193 --> 00:24:50.240
- [Shirley sighs]
- So. I find him being cuffed triggering.

451
00:24:52.826 --> 00:24:54.578
Okay. Got it.

452
00:25:02.544 --> 00:25:03.378
[sighs]

453
00:25:04.004 --> 00:25:05.005
[groans]

454
00:25:07.174 --> 00:25:08.175
[Shirley sighs]

455
00:25:12.471 --> 00:25:14.056
What happened while you were handcuffed?

456
00:25:15.015 --> 00:25:18.477
A man threatened to cut open my stomach.

457
00:25:20.521 --> 00:25:21.980
He had an electric...

458
00:25:24.316 --> 00:25:26.151
uh. carving knife.

459
00:25:31.532 --> 00:25:32.616
Badarse.

460
00:25:32.616 --> 00:25:33.742
[JK sighs]

461
00:25:34.701 --> 00:25:35.786
Brothers in cuffs.

462
00:25:39.915 --> 00:25:43.961
I don't like to be touched.

463
00:25:49.258 --> 00:25:50.968
What the fuck.

464
00:25:53.011 --> 00:25:55.013
[chattering indistinctly in French]

465
00:25:56.056 --> 00:25:59.268
[barking]

466
00:26:03.397 --> 00:26:04.648
Victor is my cousin.

467
00:26:05.858 --> 00:26:06.859
Is he?

468
00:26:07.860 --> 00:26:08.986
Nice to meet you. Victor.

469
00:26:09.945 --> 00:26:11.697
[Natasha] He was the only one
who stood by me

470
00:26:11.697 --> 00:26:14.241
when I was made pregnant by
the man at Les Arbres.

471
00:26:15.742 --> 00:26:16.827
I was 17.

472
00:26:17.870 --> 00:26:19.830
And that's... that's this man?

473
00:26:21.290 --> 00:26:22.332
[Natasha] Yes.

474
00:26:23.792 --> 00:26:25.460
Frank Harkness.

475
00:26:26.295 --> 00:26:29.631
Although. he told so many lies.
that may not be his real name.

476
00:26:31.175 --> 00:26:32.676
Well. he never let me see my son.

477
00:26:32.676 --> 00:26:38.682
So. I-I moved away and. um. I would
come back sometimes to see Bertrand.

478
00:26:39.558 --> 00:26:43.228
and he looked through me
like I didn't exist.

479
00:26:44.354 --> 00:26:46.940
We heard everyone at Les Arbres was gone.

480
00:26:48.775 --> 00:26:50.694
and she would never see Bertrand again.

481
00:26:52.029 --> 00:26:53.530
I thought you were him.

482
00:26:53.530 --> 00:26:58.410
So. I called her. followed you.

483
00:26:59.203 --> 00:27:01.496
Found Frank trying to kill you.

484
00:27:01.997 --> 00:27:05.250
And then you hit me... [speaks French]

485
00:27:06.793 --> 00:27:09.463
Why would Frank try to kill you?

486
00:27:10.047 --> 00:27:13.717
Well. I think he was destroying evidence.
and I just got in his way.

487
00:27:14.259 --> 00:27:15.886
And the bomber. what about him?

488
00:27:17.137 --> 00:27:19.139
- [Natasha] Yves.
- [River] Yves.

489
00:27:19.139 --> 00:27:22.851
[Natasha] Well. that's no surprise.
The way he was treated as a boy.

490
00:27:22.851 --> 00:27:26.146
You could see his-his hate. his anger.

491
00:27:26.730 --> 00:27:30.192
[clicks tongue] So.
you-you-you lived at Les Arbres?

492
00:27:30.943 --> 00:27:32.236
[Natasha] Yeah.

493
00:27:32.236 --> 00:27:33.862
While Bertrand was little.

494
00:27:34.738 --> 00:27:35.948
Did you paint this?

495
00:27:37.241 --> 00:27:38.325
[sighs]

496
00:27:39.326 --> 00:27:42.829
No. [chuckles] One of the other girls did.

497
00:27:43.372 --> 00:27:44.498
Other girls?

498
00:27:45.457 --> 00:27:47.084
Yes. The mothers.

499
00:27:47.084 --> 00:27:49.837
You know. there were some Russians.
a Greek.

500
00:27:49.837 --> 00:27:54.758
Uh. maybe. um. an English
and another local girl. I think.

501
00:27:55.425 --> 00:27:59.721
They have... [stammers] ...his children.
and then he makes the mothers leave

502
00:27:59.721 --> 00:28:01.515
- because that's...
- [dog barking]

503
00:28:01.515 --> 00:28:03.225
...that's how he wants things to be.

504
00:28:05.185 --> 00:28:06.812
- [speaks French]
- [Victor] I'll speak to them.

505
00:28:07.604 --> 00:28:09.648
Tell them you are not
who they think you are.

506
00:28:09.648 --> 00:28:11.275
Yeah. please.

507
00:28:13.819 --> 00:28:16.613
Wow. They really didn't like your son.
did they?

508
00:28:16.613 --> 00:28:20.742
Well. the man out there.
Bertrand put his son in the hospital

509
00:28:20.742 --> 00:28:22.327
and assaulted his daughter.

510
00:28:22.327 --> 00:28:25.122
So. we don't really blame him
for his hate.

511
00:28:26.248 --> 00:28:29.209
- Victor will calm them.
- [Victor speaks French]

512
00:28:29.209 --> 00:28:32.588
- [grunts]
- [clamoring]

513
00:28:32.588 --> 00:28:34.214
- Fuck me. Jesus.
- Run.

514
00:28:39.511 --> 00:28:41.346
[banging on door]

515
00:28:42.222 --> 00:28:44.516
- That's a big dog. [chuckles]
- [mob member grunts]

516
00:28:45.475 --> 00:28:46.935
[mob clamoring]

517
00:28:47.728 --> 00:28:48.687
[Natasha speaks French]

518
00:28:48.687 --> 00:28:50.230
[in French] It's not him!

519
00:28:50.647 --> 00:28:51.940
It's not Bertrand!

520
00:28:51.940 --> 00:28:53.233
[exclaims]

521
00:28:53.233 --> 00:28:56.278
- [handler speaks French]
- [dog growling]

522
00:28:56.278 --> 00:28:58.822
- [barking]
- [grunts]

523
00:28:58.822 --> 00:29:00.908
[clamoring continues]

524
00:29:02.576 --> 00:29:03.493
[River] Shit.

525
00:29:03.493 --> 00:29:04.870
[speaks French]

526
00:29:05.370 --> 00:29:07.998
- [grunting]
- [banging on door]

527
00:29:11.919 --> 00:29:15.088
- [mob shouts in French]
- [pants]

528
00:29:17.216 --> 00:29:20.219
- [growls. barking]
- [speaking French]

529
00:29:29.186 --> 00:29:30.187
[grunting]

530
00:29:31.355 --> 00:29:32.940
[groaning]

531
00:29:38.445 --> 00:29:39.863
[grunts. breathes sharply]

532
00:29:39.863 --> 00:29:41.949
[panting]

533
00:29:44.284 --> 00:29:46.286
[mob clamoring. shouting]

534
00:29:46.286 --> 00:29:47.871
[dog barking]

535
00:29:53.585 --> 00:29:55.087
[River] Come on.

536
00:29:56.880 --> 00:29:58.966
[clamoring continues]

537
00:30:12.938 --> 00:30:13.939
[exclaims]

538
00:30:14.439 --> 00:30:15.274
Monsieur.

539
00:30:15.274 --> 00:30:16.942
- All right. fuck off!
- [grunting]

540
00:30:17.442 --> 00:30:19.361
[moped revs. stalls]

541
00:30:19.361 --> 00:30:21.154
[River] What the fucking...

542
00:30:21.780 --> 00:30:23.156
[moped revs]

543
00:30:28.287 --> 00:30:29.371
Ah!

544
00:30:44.428 --> 00:30:46.430
[footsteps approaching]

545
00:30:52.519 --> 00:30:54.813
- Why aren't you answering your phone?
- [Catherine sighs]

546
00:30:54.813 --> 00:30:58.233
- How have you been. by the way?
- River has it. And I'm fine. Thank you.

547
00:30:59.401 --> 00:31:01.111
Why didn't Lamb just tell me that?

548
00:31:01.111 --> 00:31:02.738
So. Lamb sent you?

549
00:31:02.738 --> 00:31:05.073
Yeah. Where's David?

550
00:31:05.073 --> 00:31:06.783
Oh. luckily I moved him.

551
00:31:06.783 --> 00:31:09.536
It took Lamb all of five minutes
to work out how to find him.

552
00:31:09.536 --> 00:31:10.996
I mean. he's smarter than most.

553
00:31:10.996 --> 00:31:13.457
but he's not the only brain
on Spook Street.

554
00:31:13.457 --> 00:31:17.169
David thinks he's meeting
First Desk in a safe house.

555
00:31:17.169 --> 00:31:18.962
- Where?
- Number 25.

556
00:31:18.962 --> 00:31:21.548
- I'm cat-sitting for my neighbor.
- [sighs]

557
00:31:22.508 --> 00:31:24.510
So. how was River when you saw him?

558
00:31:24.510 --> 00:31:27.095
Mmm. He's all right considering.

559
00:31:27.095 --> 00:31:28.347
He's not answering your phone.

560
00:31:28.347 --> 00:31:30.432
He won't do. He's taken out the SIM card.

561
00:31:31.391 --> 00:31:33.060
I'm sorry Lamb told you River was dead.

562
00:31:33.060 --> 00:31:34.770
That must have been very hard.

563
00:31:34.770 --> 00:31:36.897
Yeah. it's pretty much the final straw.

564
00:31:37.439 --> 00:31:38.899
I might join you on the outside.

565
00:31:38.899 --> 00:31:41.068
[groans] You'd get very bored.

566
00:31:42.069 --> 00:31:43.654
What's the Westacres news?

567
00:31:44.321 --> 00:31:45.405
Nothing.

568
00:31:45.405 --> 00:31:47.866
Although they're not
ruling out further attacks.

569
00:31:48.575 --> 00:31:50.619
Any idea who tried to kill David?

570
00:31:50.619 --> 00:31:52.204
Just that they came from France.

571
00:31:52.204 --> 00:31:53.288
[meows]

572
00:31:53.956 --> 00:31:56.041
- Oh. hello. Pinkel.
- [meows]

573
00:31:56.041 --> 00:31:58.585
[chuckles] Are you allergic to cats?

574
00:31:59.086 --> 00:32:00.671
No. I just don't really like them.

575
00:32:01.463 --> 00:32:02.798
David?

576
00:32:05.467 --> 00:32:06.468
David?

577
00:32:08.804 --> 00:32:09.888
David?

578
00:32:10.806 --> 00:32:12.057
[Louisa] Catherine!

579
00:32:13.308 --> 00:32:15.143
The back door's open!

580
00:32:16.144 --> 00:32:17.396
Oh. my God.

581
00:32:18.564 --> 00:32:20.566
[both panting]

582
00:32:28.240 --> 00:32:29.408
Oh. fuck.

583
00:32:30.492 --> 00:32:31.827
What am I going to tell River?

584
00:32:31.827 --> 00:32:33.662
What am I gonna tell Lamb? [sighs]

585
00:32:34.496 --> 00:32:37.124
- [bomber on TV] <i>...will I be free.</i>
- [snoring]

586
00:32:37.124 --> 00:32:41.795
<i>You will suffer for the years
I spent imprisoned by your system.</i>

587
00:32:41.795 --> 00:32:44.089
[sirens wailing]

588
00:32:44.089 --> 00:32:46.300
<i>God willing. I will not be the last.</i>

589
00:32:49.511 --> 00:32:51.388
<i>You will hear from my brothers soon.</i>

590
00:32:53.015 --> 00:32:54.516
- [TV host] <i>I'm here on the...</i>
- [knocks]

591
00:32:54.516 --> 00:32:57.060
<i>...just outside of
the Westacres Shopping Center.</i>

592
00:32:57.060 --> 00:32:58.312
<i>where the mood is still...</i>

593
00:32:58.312 --> 00:33:01.398
I'm afraid I've got some bad news.
[sniffs]

594
00:33:02.566 --> 00:33:03.859
What the fuck's that?

595
00:33:04.985 --> 00:33:07.487
This? It's just a simple tussie-mussie.

596
00:33:09.239 --> 00:33:10.908
Oh. fuck off.

597
00:33:10.908 --> 00:33:12.576
It's a nosegay.

598
00:33:12.576 --> 00:33:14.870
People used to sniff them
during the great plague

599
00:33:14.870 --> 00:33:17.623
- to cancel out the stench of death.
- [sighs]

600
00:33:17.623 --> 00:33:18.916
Fuck off.

601
00:33:20.709 --> 00:33:23.170
I've asked my contacts back at the Park.

602
00:33:23.170 --> 00:33:27.549
and there isn't a single shred of evidence
that David Cartwright ever went to France.

603
00:33:28.425 --> 00:33:29.968
So. I suppose our deal is off.

604
00:33:31.428 --> 00:33:33.722
[sighs] I'm afraid so.

605
00:33:33.722 --> 00:33:35.474
Looks like I'm stuck with you.

606
00:33:36.475 --> 00:33:42.189
I did discover that his bagman went there
in the early 90s.

607
00:33:43.649 --> 00:33:44.650
Lavande?

608
00:33:45.150 --> 00:33:46.360
Yes.

609
00:33:48.028 --> 00:33:53.158
Go see Ho. and tell him I said
to find out why you're at Slough House.

610
00:33:53.158 --> 00:33:54.409
- Really?
- Well. yeah.

611
00:33:54.409 --> 00:33:55.744
Yeah. I don't want you here.

612
00:33:55.744 --> 00:34:00.832
And letting me know that Bad Sam Chapman
went to France is good enough.

613
00:34:02.709 --> 00:34:04.795
[sniffs. sighs]

614
00:34:08.966 --> 00:34:10.300
[door closes]

615
00:34:20.268 --> 00:34:21.687
[Chapman]
<i>Here you are. Take a closer look.</i>

616
00:34:22.728 --> 00:34:24.231
Sure you haven't seen him?

617
00:34:24.231 --> 00:34:25.732
He lives right across from here.

618
00:34:26.233 --> 00:34:28.193
Thirteen. Looks a bit older.

619
00:34:28.193 --> 00:34:29.862
Goes by the name of KZ.

620
00:34:29.862 --> 00:34:32.281
- Do you mean KayZee? [chuckles]
- [kids laughing]

621
00:34:32.281 --> 00:34:33.489
You know him then?

622
00:34:33.489 --> 00:34:35.701
Depends. is there money in it?

623
00:34:35.701 --> 00:34:36.909
Well. there could be.

624
00:34:37.828 --> 00:34:38.871
How about an advance then?

625
00:34:38.871 --> 00:34:40.621
I don't have any cash on me.

626
00:34:41.665 --> 00:34:45.210
And you know. I don't think
you've got anything to tell me.

627
00:34:45.210 --> 00:34:47.170
Well. we can walk you to a cashpoint.

628
00:34:49.464 --> 00:34:52.467
I'm ugly enough I don't mind
getting hit in the face. How about you?

629
00:34:53.092 --> 00:34:55.012
[phone ringing]

630
00:34:55.012 --> 00:34:56.096
[chuckles]

631
00:34:58.432 --> 00:35:01.602
- [kid] Paedo.
- [kids chuckling. clamoring]

632
00:35:01.602 --> 00:35:02.853
[Chapman] <i>Hello. trouble.</i>

633
00:35:03.353 --> 00:35:04.438
I need a meet.

634
00:35:04.438 --> 00:35:06.440
[grunts] Launderette number three.

635
00:35:06.440 --> 00:35:08.901
What if I've got
something more important to do?

636
00:35:08.901 --> 00:35:11.111
- <i>You don't.</i>
- [sighs]

637
00:35:11.737 --> 00:35:13.447
[tail] I have eyes on the old man.

638
00:35:14.865 --> 00:35:16.533
[Frank] <i>Okay. so take him out.</i>

639
00:35:17.117 --> 00:35:18.702
[sighs] He's in public now.

640
00:35:19.203 --> 00:35:23.624
<i>Let him know he's being followed.
He'll get nervous. try and hide.</i>

641
00:35:24.541 --> 00:35:27.127
<i>Kill him out of sight.
then move on to Cartwright.</i>

642
00:35:35.302 --> 00:35:36.386
[Marcus] <i>Dancer Blaine?</i>

643
00:35:37.638 --> 00:35:39.556
Got a bit of merchandise for you.

644
00:35:39.556 --> 00:35:41.517
[Dancer] <i>Who sent you?</i>

645
00:35:41.517 --> 00:35:42.976
No one.

646
00:35:42.976 --> 00:35:44.520
<i>How do you know about me?</i>

647
00:35:44.520 --> 00:35:46.522
<i>I'm MI5.</i>

648
00:35:47.231 --> 00:35:48.440
Is this a sting?

649
00:35:49.191 --> 00:35:52.861
<i>Not much of a sting if I tell you
I'm MI5 from the off. right?</i>

650
00:35:54.071 --> 00:35:55.739
Fair point. [inhales sharply]

651
00:35:57.241 --> 00:35:59.409
- [grunts]
- [door lock buzzes]

652
00:36:04.915 --> 00:36:07.125
[door unlocks]

653
00:36:12.047 --> 00:36:12.881
All right.

654
00:36:19.012 --> 00:36:20.722
- [sighs]
- [door closes]

655
00:36:21.932 --> 00:36:22.933
[sniffs]

656
00:36:30.566 --> 00:36:32.651
Do you know why they call me Dancer?

657
00:36:33.527 --> 00:36:35.112
'Cause you're into ballroom dancing?

658
00:36:36.363 --> 00:36:41.702
And also because I sense danger
and dance right around it.

659
00:36:42.369 --> 00:36:46.999
Now. serving MI5 officer.
well. that screams trouble to me.

660
00:36:48.709 --> 00:36:50.169
Why do you want to sell me a gun?

661
00:36:50.169 --> 00:36:51.962
- I need money. right and fast.
- So. rob a bank.

662
00:36:51.962 --> 00:36:54.256
If you don't want the gun.
fine by me. I'll take it elsewhere.

663
00:36:54.256 --> 00:36:56.592
No. you won't. You need the cash.

664
00:36:56.592 --> 00:36:58.218
That's the other thing
about being a dancer.

665
00:36:58.218 --> 00:37:00.053
You learn to read people.
Anticipate their moves.

666
00:37:00.053 --> 00:37:02.431
- And I can tell you've got a good heart.
- [scoffs]

667
00:37:02.431 --> 00:37:04.391
But you're all out of moves.

668
00:37:08.812 --> 00:37:10.272
[bag unzips]

669
00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:14.735
Beretta M9.

670
00:37:14.735 --> 00:37:18.113
Beat out the Sig Sauer P226
to become the primary sidearm

671
00:37:18.113 --> 00:37:21.825
of the US Army from 1985 to present.

672
00:37:25.746 --> 00:37:27.331
- Three grand.
- It's worth five.

673
00:37:27.331 --> 00:37:30.375
Yeah. No. I can sell it for five.
That's how profit works.

674
00:37:32.794 --> 00:37:34.171
[clicks tongue]
All right. four and a half.

675
00:37:34.171 --> 00:37:35.255
Three.

676
00:37:36.340 --> 00:37:37.424
- Four.
- Three.

677
00:37:38.175 --> 00:37:39.635
- Three and a half.
- Three.

678
00:37:43.138 --> 00:37:45.682
[chuckles. inhales deeply]

679
00:37:47.601 --> 00:37:48.977
- Three.
- Perfect.

680
00:37:49.478 --> 00:37:50.979
[chuckles]

681
00:37:50.979 --> 00:37:54.024
- Great negotiating.
- [sighs]

682
00:37:54.024 --> 00:37:55.609
[cash rustling]

683
00:37:58.487 --> 00:37:59.696
[machine whirring]

684
00:38:07.704 --> 00:38:08.872
[phone ringing]

685
00:38:14.044 --> 00:38:15.045
[sniffs]

686
00:38:16.213 --> 00:38:18.298
Any time this year would be great.

687
00:38:18.298 --> 00:38:19.383
[Chapman] <i>Picked up a tail.</i>

688
00:38:20.259 --> 00:38:21.593
[Jackson] <i>Where are you?</i>

689
00:38:21.593 --> 00:38:23.345
Leading them away from you.

690
00:38:24.137 --> 00:38:27.599
<i>Could be a case I'm working
looking for a 13-year-old.</i>

691
00:38:27.599 --> 00:38:28.517
<i>Runaway.</i>

692
00:38:28.517 --> 00:38:31.186
Got mixed up with the wrong crowd.
Just faced some of them down.

693
00:38:31.186 --> 00:38:33.230
- Could be them.
- <i>Uh. it's not.</i>

694
00:38:33.230 --> 00:38:36.692
<i>Someone tried to whack
David Cartwright last night.</i>

695
00:38:36.692 --> 00:38:38.235
Shit. Who?

696
00:38:38.235 --> 00:38:41.363
Uh. I don't know. but the old bastard
blew him away with a shotgun.

697
00:38:41.363 --> 00:38:43.866
- <i>Anyone come looking for you?</i>
- [sighs] Not yet.

698
00:38:44.783 --> 00:38:46.493
I'll head to fallback number two.

699
00:38:47.160 --> 00:38:49.413
<i>I'll have the Slow Horses follow you
from the market</i>

700
00:38:49.413 --> 00:38:51.582
<i>in case your tail makes a move.</i>

701
00:38:52.082 --> 00:38:53.083
[line clicks]

702
00:38:54.376 --> 00:38:56.670
[breathes heavily]

703
00:39:11.351 --> 00:39:13.353
[phone ringing]

704
00:39:16.899 --> 00:39:18.192
Nice of you to call me back.

705
00:39:18.192 --> 00:39:21.278
Lamb called. He needs us as a backup
for a meet with Bad Sam Chapman.

706
00:39:21.278 --> 00:39:24.114
<i>He said to tail him from the market
to fallback number two.</i>

707
00:39:24.114 --> 00:39:25.574
[Marcus] Yeah. that's the old garage.

708
00:39:26.366 --> 00:39:28.827
Actually. I'm not far.
All right. be there soon as.

709
00:39:28.827 --> 00:39:30.579
[Shirley] <i>Make sure you come packing heat.</i>

710
00:39:30.579 --> 00:39:32.206
Oh. no. You can't.

711
00:39:32.873 --> 00:39:33.874
Shut up.

712
00:40:44.945 --> 00:40:45.946
[Marcus] Shirley!

713
00:40:47.072 --> 00:40:48.073
Shirley!

714
00:40:49.283 --> 00:40:51.743
Fucking hell.
Do you wanna draw any more attention?

715
00:40:52.536 --> 00:40:55.247
[sighs] Chapman's 200 yards ahead.

716
00:40:56.456 --> 00:40:57.457
[sighs]

717
00:40:57.457 --> 00:41:00.377
All right. Where's the tail?

718
00:41:00.377 --> 00:41:02.546
I thought I saw him. but he's disappeared.

719
00:41:03.130 --> 00:41:05.048
Probably saw me coming and scarpered.

720
00:41:05.549 --> 00:41:06.967
I mean. that hat would do it.

721
00:41:08.760 --> 00:41:10.470
[pedestrians. shoppers scream]

722
00:41:10.470 --> 00:41:12.806
[clamoring]

723
00:41:13.974 --> 00:41:15.017
[Marcus] Shit.

724
00:41:15.642 --> 00:41:18.145
- Are you all right?
- [groans] No.

725
00:41:18.145 --> 00:41:20.355
Fucking hell. [groans]

726
00:41:22.482 --> 00:41:24.776
Fucking hell. [grunts]

727
00:41:27.905 --> 00:41:29.031
Are you okay?

728
00:41:29.031 --> 00:41:30.699
[grunts] I'm all right.

729
00:41:31.283 --> 00:41:32.868
Fuck. [pants]

730
00:41:34.661 --> 00:41:35.829
[panting]

731
00:41:45.839 --> 00:41:48.050
- [line ringing]
- Come on. come on. come on.

732
00:41:49.176 --> 00:41:50.344
I can't seem to shake him.

733
00:41:50.344 --> 00:41:52.429
- <i>Abort.</i>
- No. keep moving.

734
00:41:52.429 --> 00:41:54.306
- <i>I'll be there.</i>
- Okay.

735
00:41:58.352 --> 00:42:01.021
[panting]

736
00:42:25.462 --> 00:42:28.423
[panting]

737
00:42:52.990 --> 00:42:54.324
[door rattles]

738
00:43:04.418 --> 00:43:05.669
[tail] Come out. old man.

739
00:43:08.172 --> 00:43:10.966
- It's over. Let's go.
- [grunts]

740
00:43:11.550 --> 00:43:12.718
[both grunt]

741
00:43:12.718 --> 00:43:13.635
[sighs]

742
00:43:15.179 --> 00:43:16.180
[grunts]

743
00:43:17.806 --> 00:43:20.809
[both grunting]

744
00:43:26.231 --> 00:43:27.232
[groans]

745
00:43:32.154 --> 00:43:34.156
- [screams]
- [groans]

